			>
			<DIV>Wow, a 300 hp buff&nbsp; BB . Sure it's a nice buff, but it still doesn't bring equal&nbsp; hps&nbsp;compared to &nbsp;a warrior&nbsp; hps, no where close, it's a part damage shield ac buff too. Even then, so what? It certainly isn't a uber buff compared to many others. SoE want's us to tank interchangeably in groups and has wanted that for a while. Since they see us as equal in that envirioment, they didn't take your "prefered tank" spot in groups, they never saw you as haveing such. That's an issue you will have to take up with SoE.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>By the way BB,&nbsp;I was agreeing with Frodlin's statement about gaps in raiding boss mobs per soloing,&nbsp;discuss your disagreement&nbsp;with him if you don't like it, it was his suggestion. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Your&nbsp;idea&nbsp; that not all warriors raid therefore they should be able to solo like knights. Conjointly some knights do raid, perhaps they should tank raid bosses like warriors? Afterall they might have too, since not all warriors raid. That's a dangerous loophole you would create.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Being equally desireable in groups achieves xp, and gear, and&nbsp;the like,&nbsp;for everyone. Soloing is an over rated option that&nbsp;I personally no longer fine even remotely enjoyable. I do it to kill time between raids or to maybe finish off an aa. I view 'soloing" as a type of barametor. If we get an over pull, I know if we have others who can solo, that they can pull one off and deal with it. A warrior would tank the first one and I could peel off the second. It's not as effective as a chanter or bard mezzing but it is cc of a sort.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Do&nbsp;I think warriors could use some sort of utility help? Sure&nbsp;I have stated as much, I think they should be atributes that make them more atractive to grouping rather than being able to solo. That's partly where we diverge BB. I think you need help in group settings more than you need it in solo settings.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;Am I a tank plus in groups? By nature of my duality yes&nbsp;I am, that is an aspect that become more and more apparent with each addtional level, spell, and aa. Something like that is very difficult to balance. D and&nbsp;D has these problems all the time with some classes. They limit levels and or restrict what races can play them because they become so overwelming at higher levels of game play.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;EQ did try xp penalties but they didn't place limits on levels cause EQ is a live action game and haveing some people able to get some levels where other couldn't would generally limit game play for those who chose those classes. Wich would defeat the purpose of haveing so many classes anyhow. If I can't get passed level 50 as an sk I wouldn't be able to do certain zones. I would choose a class where&nbsp;I could and so at high end you would only have maybe a half dozen classes.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>How to try to balance fun game play for those who wish to be a dual class vs general classes, when the nature of dual classes power up so dramtically at higher levels. That has always been at the core of these issues, defensive for warriors was one way they tried to balance it. Ensureing warriors at least a spot in raid forces. However, sooner or later, as the duel classes increase in levels, holding them back isn't as plausable because everyone knows what those classes&nbsp;can be capable of.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Wich goes back to the orginal statement made by BB.&nbsp;&nbsp;Maybe Verant, all those years ago, made a mistake&nbsp;creating duel class characters.</DIV>	
